DIE-OFF, AVIAN - ICELAND: (WESTLAND) BOTULISM SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 17 Jun 2014 [ProMED apologizes for the delayed post]
Source: Grapevine [edited]
http://grapevine.is/news/2014/06/17/disease-likely-explanation-for-mysterious-bird-deaths/


The sudden and inexplicable deaths of dozens of birds is probably linked to a disease, says an Icelandic ornithologist.

"Everything points to a disease or some other contagion at work when many adult birds die within a short period of time," said Gunnar Thor Hallgrimsson, an ornithologist and the director of the Southwest Iceland Nature Research Institute, to Visir.

Gunnar points out that in other countries, mass bird deaths are more common, and are usually the result of the bacterium _Clostridium botulinum_, better known as the organism which causes botulism.

"There is no reason to rule out this possibility, even though [botulism] is not known to be present in Iceland," he said, cautioning that further investigations would be needed to get to the bottom of the case.

As reported, close to 100 dead birds -- most of them eiders, kittiwakes and cormorants -- have been found dead near a nesting area in Frotharrif, located on the Snaefellsnes peninsula in west Iceland [Westland region]. Samples of the birds will be sent to the US for further analysis, but for now, the cause of the die-off remains a mystery.

[Byline: Paul Fontaine]

