[Avian botulism is a paralytic disease caused by ingestion of a toxin produced by the bacteria _Clostridium botulinum_. These bacteria are widespread in soil and require warm temperatures, a protein source, and an anaerobic (no oxygen) environment in order to become active and produce toxin.

Outside North America, the 1st outbreaks of botulism in wild birds were recorded in Australia in 1934, in Russia in 1957, and in Europe in 1963, 1st in Sweden and shortly after in Denmark, Great Britain, and the Netherlands. Botulism was also confirmed in South Africa (1965), New Zealand (1971), Japan (1973), Argentina (1979) and Brazil (1981). (For more information, see: http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/PDF/pub07_waterbirds_part4.2.3.pdf.)

Although no evidence is presented to support the argument that this episode may be due to botulism, an outbreak investigation considering the possibility is warranted. - Mod.PMB

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2594607,40261.]
